-- PRESS DIGEST - Wall Street Journal - July 2
-- 
-- Wed Jul 02, 2014 12:58AM EDT
-- None



July 2 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Wall Street Journal. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

* In the Supreme Court term that just concluded, Chief Justice John Roberts joined with liberal colleagues to draw some of the court's major decisions toward the middle. (http://on.wsj.com/1qiAdjZ)  * Ukraine began an all-out effort to rout Russian-backed separatists and reclaim its eastern border, in a high-stakes bet that Moscow won't intervene militarily to counter its new onslaught. (http://on.wsj.com/1qwwqBg)  * As talks between Iran and six major powers on limiting its nuclear program enter the final stages of diplomacy this week, global companies are fact-finding, meeting with potential Iranian partners and jockeying for position should an end to sanctions open the isolated market. (http://on.wsj.com/VapInv)  * James Dimon, chairman and chief executive of J.P. Morgan, told employees and shareholders he has been diagnosed with throat cancer, that the prognosis is excellent and that he will continue to be actively involved in the company during his treatment. (http://on.wsj.com/1miWePH)  * Fidelity Investments and other asset managers are telling U.S. clients who live outside the country that they can no longer buy or trade mutual funds in their brokerage accounts. Stephen Austin, a spokesman for the financial-services firm, said the change, effective Aug. 1, was prompted by "today's continually evolving global regulatory environment," but he said it wasn't in response to a specific issue. (http://on.wsj.com/1jI54Rc)  * William Ackman's Pershing Square said it has hired Credit Suisse <CSGN.VX>, known for defending companies against activist investors, to help Valeant <VRX.TO> take over Allergan <AGN.N>. (http://on.wsj.com/1lRmDTz)  * The Federal Trade Commission sued T-Mobile USA Inc [TUII.UL], accusing the wireless carrier of billing consumers hundreds of millions of dollars in bogus charges on their wireless bills. (http://on.wsj.com/1pInQzW)  * Cheniere Energy Inc <LNG.A> is abandoning its plan to issue 30 million shares to executives and other employees after running into opposition from investors. The company said in court filings that it would withdraw a compensation plan that it had submitted for shareholder approval. (http://on.wsj.com/1iTBpK2)  * Nestlé SA <NESN.VX> has sold its Juicy Juice brand to buyout firm Brynwood Partners, the latest move in the Swiss food giant's push to simplify its sprawling U.S. business by shedding languishing brands. (http://on.wsj.com/1qiZvyn)  * BNP Paribas SA <BNPP.PA> on Tuesday sought to allay concern about its ability to weather a $9 billion settlement with U.S. authorities. The bank has said the penalties would shave just a little more than a half a percentage point from its core tier-one capital ratio. The ratio is a key gauge of a bank's financial health. (http://on.wsj.com/1z6CEdC)